{"cursor":"18137","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"'Scientific notation' is a way of writing numbers that are too big or too small\nto be conveniently written in decimal form. Scientific notation has a number of\nuseful properties and is commonly used in calculators and by scientists,\nmathematicians and engineers.\n\nIn scientific notation all numbers are written in the form of\n: a \\times 10^b\n(a times ten raised to the power of b), where the exponent b is an integer, and\nthe coefficient a is any real number (however, see normalized notation below),\ncalled the [[significand]] or [[mantissa]]. The term \"mantissa\" may cause\nconfusion, however, because it can also refer to the fractional part of the\ncommon logarithm. If the number is negative then a minus sign precedes a (as in\nordinary decimal notation).\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float:right\"\n|-\n!Standard decimal notation !Normalized scientific notation\n|- 2\n|\n|- 300\n|\n|- 4,321.768\n|\n|- -53,000\n|\n|- 6,720,000,000\n|\n|- .2\n|\n|- .000 000 007 51\n|\n|}\n\nDecimal floating point is a computer arithmetic system closely related to\nscientific notation.\n","linknr":279,"url":"Exponential_notation","recorded":1362899585,"links":48,"instances":["mathematical_constant","exponentiation","programming_language","mathematics","programming_language","punctuation","mathematics","programming","programming_language","mathematics"],"pdf":["http://www.unicode.org/charts/PDF/U2300.pdf","http://education.ti.com/downloads/guidebooks/sdk/83p/sdk83pguide.pdf","http://hps.org/documents/2010_midyear_author-submission-guidelines.pdf","https://darchive.mblwhoilibrary.org/bitstream/1912/665/1/WHOI-76-59.pdf","http://www.gnsphysics.com/mathreview.pdf"],"categories":["Numeral systems","Measurement","Notation"],"headings":["{{anchor|Normalized notation}}Normalized notation","Engineering notation","Significant figures","{{anchor|E notation}}E notation","Order of magnitude","Use of spaces","Converting